Khalil: All right, crafters, what is going on? You've made it here to the software essentialist, the training, and it is time to level up. Yes. Yes, it is. So we're going to do here in this very first module, this introduction is we're going to go over the big picture for the whole course. We're going to do that from top to bottom, because sometimes it's really good for you to get a sense of what is coming.

So the main problem that developers have, the reason why you're here would make sense, is this kind of nagging feeling of just a lack of full confidence in your own design abilities.

There's this feeling of, am I doing things [00:01:00] right? And the reality is you want to be the type of person who feels confident in your own design decisions, your architecture decisions, testing and strategy decisions, because those are the things that really matter.

At the end of the day, you're always going to get new requirements. You're always going to get new challenges that you're going to need to face. And those challenges are not always going to be the same. They're going to be dynamic, and they're going to require bespoke ways of approaching them. What we need to do here is develop what I call the main skill, problem decomposition.

I believe that great programmers, like philosophers, have metacognition, which is awareness of your own thinking, you have the ability to know how you're solving problems, how you're thinking about solving problems.

And you can refine the way that you're solving problems. So at the end of the day, what we want to do here is we want to develop really solid mental models for how to consistently approach your work.

That's going [00:02:00] to give you the ability to solve pretty much any problem you run into in a consistent way. That might sound like a big promise, but it is possible if you have really good mental models.

So on my side a large motivation why I even wanted to make this course and put it together was because I've been piecing and crunching together this whole thing of how to do software development well for a while now.

And I've been trying to create my own conceptual understanding of it. And I think I've landed on some really incredible stuff here that I'm excited to share with you.

So now let's talk about the course goals. Alright, what are we going to do here? So I want to convert you, wherever you are right now, into a confident crafter who knows what they're doing. We want to learn the mental models for how to think about software development and what it even means for you to be a software developer.

And we are going to do this with what I call the 12 essentials, which are going to give us a strong baseline in the things that [00:03:00] actually matter. And that's testing, design, architecture, and strategy.

And this is going to cover important parts from a number of key topics.

If I mention a few of the key parts of this course, it's going to be your ability to use systems thinking, this thing called the guess points, which is how we can break apart and decompose problems.

And this other tool called faster, which is like a design method, something you could use to actually convert a problem into action steps that you need to perform to systematically break down problems, right?

And we're going to be getting into design and testing strategies along the way.

And we will get into testing and we'll get into design. And we will get into testing strategies

So now let's talk about what to expect. This is a programming course, but it is very different from other programming courses. We're not just going to be focused in on the topics, particularly where a lot of other courses are focused in on topics.

This is more about you turning into the type of person who could think through problems; this is more about turning into the type of person who could think through problems.

Now let's talk about the program outline, right? So there's a couple of different sections to this course.

In the metaphysics, we're [00:07:00] going to get very clear on foundational ideas. What even is software? Why do we write software? Who are we writing software for? Now, the phases of craftship. This is where we're going to put the mental models into practice.
